# Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the task-management Next.js project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics Package
- Used pnpm (the project's package manager) to install `@vercel/analytics@2.0.1`
- Package added to dependencies in `package.json`
- Lock file `pnpm-lock.yaml` updated with new dependencies

### 2. Integrated Analytics Component
- Modified `app/layout.tsx` to import and render the Analytics component
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Placed `<Analytics />` component in the root layout's body, right after `<SpeedInsights />`
- Follows the official Next.js App Router integration pattern from Vercel documentation

### 3. Implementation Details
- The Analytics component is placed in the root layout to track all pages across the application
- Auto-no-ops outside Vercel environments (no environment variables required)
- When deployed to Vercel, it will automatically record visitor analytics per route
- Consistent with the existing SpeedInsights integration pattern already in the project
- Added descriptive comment explaining the Analytics functionality

## Files Modified
- `task-management/app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics import and component
- `task-management/package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `task-management/pnpm-lock.yaml` - Updated with new package dependencies

## Verification
- ✅ TypeScript compilation passes with no errors
- ✅ ESLint passes with no errors on modified files
- ✅ Integration follows official Vercel documentation (fetched 2026-06-26)
- ✅ Follows existing code patterns (matches SpeedInsights integration)
- ✅ Dependencies installed and lock file updated

## Notes
- The Analytics component will only collect data when the app is deployed to Vercel
- No additional configuration needed; analytics will be accessible from the Vercel project dashboard
- The implementation is framework-specific for Next.js App Router as per the documentation
